# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rigid-body-dynamics-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **Euler's rotation equations** are a vectorial quasilinear first-order ordinary differential equation describing the rotation of a rigid body, using a rotating reference frame with angular velocity ω whose axes are fixed to the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] They are named in honour of Leonhard Euler.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] In the absence of applied torques, one obtains the Euler top.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] When the torques are due to gravity, there are special cases when the motion of the top is integrable.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] where *M* is the applied torques and *I* is the inertia matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] The vector ${\dot {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}$ is the angular acceleration.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] Again, note that all quantities are defined in the rotating reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] where *Mk* are the components of the applied torques, *Ik* are the principal moments of inertia and ω*k* are the components of the angular velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] For point particles such that the internal forces are central forces, this may be derived using Newton's second law.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] In the inertial frame, the differential equation is not always helpful in solving for the motion of a general rotating rigid body, as both **I**in and **ω** can change during the motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] One may instead change to a coordinate frame fixed in the rotating body, in which the moment of inertia tensor is constant.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] Using a reference frame such as that at the center of mass, the frame's position drops out of the equations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] and so the cross product arises, see time derivative in rotating reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] Now $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {I} {\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is substituted and the time derivatives are taken in the rotating frame, while realizing that the particle positions and the inertia tensor does not depend on time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] The equations are also derived from Newton's laws in the discussion of the resultant torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] When choosing a frame so that its axes are aligned with the principal axes of the inertia tensor, its component matrix is diagonal, which further simplifies calculations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] Also in some frames not tied to the body can it be possible to obtain such simple (diagonal tensor) equations for the rate of change of the angular momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] Then **ω** must be the angular velocity for rotation of that frames axes instead of the rotation of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] It is however still required that the chosen axes are still principal axes of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] The resulting form of the Euler rotation equations is useful for rotation-symmetric objects that allow some of the principal axes of rotation to be chosen freely.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] Torque-free precessions are non-trivial solution for the situation where the torque on the right hand side is zero.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] When **I** is not constant in the external reference frame (i.e. the body is moving and its inertia tensor is not constantly diagonal) then **I** cannot be pulled through the derivative operator acting on **L**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] In this case **I**(*t*) and **ω**(*t*) do change together in such a way that the derivative of their product is still zero.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] This motion can be visualized by Poinsot's construction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] The Euler equations can be generalized to any simple Lie algebra.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] The original Euler equations come from fixing the Lie algebra to be ${\mathfrak {so}}(3)$ , with generators ${t_{1},t_{2},t_{3}}$ satisfying the relation $[t_{a},t_{b}]=\epsilon _{abc}t_{c}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] This expression generalizes readily to an arbitrary simple Lie algebra, say in the standard classification of simple Lie algebras.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] The Euler equations for rigid body dynamics can be derived from the Euler–Arnold equation, a class of partial differential equations (PDEs) that describe the geodesic flow on infinite-dimensional Lie groups equipped with right-invariant metrics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] Also, the Euler equations of fluid dynamics can be derived from the same Euler-Arnold equation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/euler-s-equations-rigid-body-dynamics] This can also be viewed as a Lax pair formulation of the generalized Euler equations, suggesting their integrability.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A **gyroscope** (from Ancient Greek γῦρος *gŷros* 'round' and σκοπέω *skopéō* 'to look') is a device used for measuring or maintaining orientation and angular velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It is a spinning wheel or disc in which the axis of rotation (spin axis) is free to assume any orientation by itself.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] When rotating, the orientation of this axis is unaffected by tilting or rotation of the mounting, due to the conservation of angular momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyroscopes based on other operating principles also exist, such as the microchip-packaged MEMS gyroscopes found in electronic devices (sometimes called **gyrometers**), solid-state ring lasers, fibre optic gyroscopes, and the extremely sensitive quantum gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Applications of gyroscopes include inertial navigation systems, such as in the Hubble Space Telescope, or inside the steel hull of a submerged submarine.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Due to their precision, gyroscopes are also used in gyrotheodolites to maintain direction in tunnel mining.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyroscopes can be used to construct gyrocompasses, which complement or replace magnetic compasses (in ships, aircraft and spacecraft, vehicles in general), to assist in stability (bicycles, motorcycles, and ships; known as **gyrostabilization**) or be used as part of an inertial guidance system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] MEMS (microelectromechanical system) gyroscopes are popular in some consumer electronics, such as smartphones.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A gyroscope is an instrument, consisting of a wheel mounted into two or three gimbals providing pivoted supports, for allowing the wheel to rotate about a single axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A set of three gimbals, one mounted on the other with orthogonal pivot axes, may be used to allow a wheel mounted on the innermost gimbal to have an orientation remaining independent of the orientation, in space, of its support.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In the case of a gyroscope with two gimbals, the outer gimbal, which is the gyroscope frame, is mounted so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane determined by the support.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This outer gimbal possesses one degree of rotational freedom and its axis possesses none.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The second (inner) gimbal is mounted in the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal) so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane that is always perpendicular to the pivotal axis of the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This inner gimbal has two degrees of rotational freedom.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The axle of the spinning wheel (the rotor) defines the spin axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The rotor is constrained to spin about an axis, which is always perpendicular to the axis of the inner gimbal.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] So the rotor possesses three degrees of rotational freedom and its axis possesses two.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The rotor responds to a force applied to the input axis by a reaction force to the output axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A gyroscope flywheel will roll or resist about the output axis depending upon whether the output gimbals are of a free or fixed configuration.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] An example of some free-output-gimbal devices is the attitude control gyroscopes used to sense or measure the pitch, roll and yaw attitude angles in a spacecraft or aircraft.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The centre of gravity of the rotor can be in a fixed position.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The rotor simultaneously spins about one axis and is capable of oscillating about the two other axes, and it is free to turn in any direction about the fixed point (except for its inherent resistance caused by rotor spin).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Some gyroscopes have mechanical equivalents substituted for one or more of the elements.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] For example, the spinning rotor may be suspended in a fluid, instead of being mounted in gimbals.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A control moment gyroscope (CMG) is an example of a fixed-output-gimbal device that is used on spacecraft to hold or maintain a desired attitude angle or pointing direction using the gyroscopic resistance force.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In some special cases, the outer gimbal (or its equivalent) may be omitted so that the rotor has only two degrees of freedom.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In other cases, the centre of gravity of the rotor may be offset from the axis of oscillation, and thus the centre of gravity of the rotor and the centre of suspension of the rotor may not coincide.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Essentially, a gyroscope is a top combined with a pair of gimbals.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Tops were invented in many different civilizations, including classical Greece, Rome, and China.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Most of these were not utilized as instruments.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The first known apparatus similar to a gyroscope (the "Whirling Speculum" or "Serson's Speculum") was invented by John Serson in 1743.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It was used as a level, to locate the horizon in foggy or misty conditions.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The first instrument used more like an actual gyroscope was made by Johann Bohnenberger of Germany, who first wrote about it in 1817.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Bohnenberger's machine was based on a rotating massive sphere.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Johnson developed a similar device that was based on a rotating disc.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The French mathematician Pierre-Simon Laplace, working at the École Polytechnique in Paris, recommended the machine for use as a teaching aid, and thus it came to the attention of Léon Foucault.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In 1852, Foucault used it in an experiment demonstrating the rotation of the Earth.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It was Foucault who gave the device its modern name, in an experiment to see (Greek *skopeein* 'to see') the Earth's rotation (Greek *gyros* 'circle, rotation'), which was visible in the 8 to 10 minutes before friction slowed the spinning rotor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In the 1860s, the advent of electric motors made it possible for a gyroscope to spin indefinitely; this led to the first prototype heading indicators, and a rather more complicated device, the gyrocompass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The first functional gyrocompass was patented in 1904 by German inventor Hermann Anschütz-Kaempfe.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] American Elmer Sperry followed with his own design later that year, and other nations soon realized the military importance of the invention—in an age in which naval prowess was the most significant measure of military power—and created their own gyroscope industries.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The Sperry Gyroscope Company quickly expanded to provide aircraft and naval stabilizers as well, and other gyroscope developers followed suit.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Hurst Mfg Co of Indianapolis started producing the "Hurst gyroscope" a toy gyroscope with a pull string and pedestal.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Manufacture was at some point switched to Chandler Mfg Co (still branded Hurst).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The product was later renamed to a "Chandler gyroscope", presumably because Chandler Mfg Co. took over rights to the gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Chandler continued to produce the toy until the company was purchased by TEDCO Inc. in 1982.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The gyroscope is still produced by TEDCO today.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Similar principles were later employed in the development of inertial navigation systems for ballistic missiles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] During World War II, the gyroscope became the prime component for aircraft and anti-aircraft gun sights.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] After the war, the race to miniaturize gyroscopes for guided missiles and weapons navigation systems resulted in the development and manufacturing of so-called **midget gyroscopes** that weighed less than 3 ounces (85 g) and had a diameter of approximately 1 inch (2.5 cm).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Some of these miniaturized gyroscopes could reach a speed of 24,000 revolutions per minute in less than 10 seconds.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyroscopes continue to be an engineering challenge.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] For example, the axle bearings have to be extremely accurate.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A small amount of friction is deliberately introduced to the bearings, since otherwise an accuracy of better than $10^{-7}$ of an inch (2.5 nm) would be required.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Three-axis MEMS-based gyroscopes are also used in portable electronic devices such as tablets, smartphones, and smartwatches.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This adds to the 3-axis acceleration sensing ability available on previous generations of devices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Together these sensors provide 6 component motion sensing; accelerometers for X, Y, and Z movement, and gyroscopes for measuring the extent and rate of rotation in space (roll, pitch and yaw).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Some devices additionally incorporate a magnetometer to provide absolute angular measurements relative to the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Newer MEMS-based inertial measurement units incorporate up to all nine axes of sensing in a single integrated circuit package, providing inexpensive and widely available motion sensing.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] All spinning objects have gyroscopic properties.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The main properties that an object can experience in any gyroscopic motion are rigidity in space and precession.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Rigidity in space describes the principle that a gyroscope remains in the fixed position on the plane in which it is spinning, unaffected by the Earth's rotation. such as with a rotating bike wheel.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Early forms of gyroscope (not then known by the name) were used to demonstrate the principle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] where $\phi '$ represents precession, $\psi '$ is represented by spin, $\theta$ is the nutation angle, and I represents inertia along its respective axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This relation is only valid when the moments along the Y and Z axes are equal to 0.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The equation can be further reduced noting that the angular velocity along the z-axis is equal to the sum of the precession and the spin: $\omega _{z}=\phi '\cos \theta +\psi '$ , Where $\omega _{z}$ represents the angular velocity along the z axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyroscopic precession is torque induced.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It is the rate of change of the angular momentum that is produced by the applied torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Precession produces counterintuitive dynamic results such as a spinning top not falling over.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Precession is used in aerospace applications for sensing changes of attitude and direction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A Steadicam rig was employed during the filming of the 1983 film *Return of the Jedi*, in conjunction with two gyroscopes for extra stabilization, to film the background plates for the speeder bike chase.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Steadicam inventor Garrett Brown operated the shot, walking through a redwood forest, running the camera at one frame per second.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] When projected at 24 frames per second, it gave the impression of flying through the air at perilous speeds.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The heading indicator or directional gyro has an axis of rotation that is set horizontally, pointing north.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Unlike a magnetic compass, it does not seek north.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] When being used in an airplane, for example, it will slowly drift away from north and will need to be reoriented periodically, using a magnetic compass as a reference.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Unlike a directional gyro or heading indicator, a gyrocompass seeks north.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It detects the rotation of the Earth about its axis and seeks the *true* north, rather than the *magnetic* north.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyrocompasses usually have built-in damping to prevent overshoot when re-calibrating from sudden movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] By determining an object's acceleration and integrating over time, the velocity of the object can be calculated.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Integrating again, position can be determined.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The simplest accelerometer is a weight that is free to move horizontally, which is attached to a spring and a device to measure the tension in the spring.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This can be improved by introducing a counteracting force to push the weight back and to measure the force needed to prevent the weight from moving.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A more complicated design consists of a gyroscope with a weight on one of the axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The device will react to the force generated by the weight when it is accelerated, by integrating that force to produce a velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A **gyrostat** consists of a massive flywheel concealed in a solid casing.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Its behaviour on a table, or with various modes of suspension or support, serves to illustrate the curious reversal of the ordinary laws of static equilibrium due to the gyrostatic behaviour of the interior invisible flywheel when rotated rapidly.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The first gyrostat was designed by Lord Kelvin to illustrate the more complicated state of motion of a spinning body when free to wander about on a horizontal plane, like a top spun on the pavement, or a bicycle on the road.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Kelvin also made use of gyrostats to develop mechanical theories of the elasticity of matter and of the ether.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In modern continuum mechanics there is a variety of these models, based on ideas of Lord Kelvin.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] They represent a specific type of Cosserat theories (suggested for the first time by Eugène Cosserat and François Cosserat), which can be used for description of artificially made smart materials as well as of other complex media.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] One of them, so-called Kelvin's medium, has the same equations as magnetic insulators near the state of magnetic saturation in the approximation of quasimagnetostatics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In modern times, the gyrostat concept is used in the design of attitude control systems for orbiting spacecraft and satellites.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] For instance, the Mir space station had three pairs of internally mounted flywheels known as *gyrodynes* or control moment gyroscopes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In physics, there are several systems whose dynamical equations resemble the equations of motion of a gyrostat.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) gyroscope is a miniaturized gyroscope found in electronic devices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It takes the idea of the Foucault pendulum and uses a vibrating element.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This kind of gyroscope was first used in military applications but has since been adopted for increasing commercial use.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The hemispherical resonator gyroscope (HRG), also called a wine-glass gyroscope or mushroom gyro, makes use of a thin solid-state hemispherical shell, anchored by a thick stem.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This shell is driven to a flexural resonance by electrostatic forces generated by electrodes which are deposited directly onto separate fused-quartz structures that surround the shell.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyroscopic effect is obtained from the inertial property of the flexural standing waves.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A vibrating structure gyroscope (VSG), also called a Coriolis vibratory gyroscope (CVG), uses a resonator made of different metallic alloys.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It takes a position between the low-accuracy, low-cost MEMS gyroscope and the higher-accuracy and higher-cost fiber optic gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Accuracy parameters are increased by using low-intrinsic damping materials, resonator vacuumization, and digital electronics to reduce temperature dependent drift and instability of control signals.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] High quality wine-glass resonators are used for precise sensors like HRG.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A dynamically tuned gyroscope (DTG) is a rotor suspended by a universal joint with flexure pivots.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The flexure spring stiffness is independent of spin rate.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] However, the dynamic inertia (from the gyroscopic reaction effect) from the gimbal provides negative spring stiffness proportional to the square of the spin speed (Howe and Savet, 1964; Lawrence, 1998).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Therefore, at a particular speed, called the tuning speed, the two moments cancel each other, freeing the rotor from torque, a necessary condition for an ideal gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A ring laser gyroscope relies on the Sagnac effect to measure rotation by measuring the shifting interference pattern of a beam split into two separate beams which travel around the ring in opposite directions.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] When the Boeing 757-200 entered service in 1983, it was equipped with the first suitable ring laser gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This gyroscope took many years to develop, and the experimental models went through many changes before it was deemed ready for production by the engineers and managers of Honeywell and Boeing.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It was an outcome of the competition with mechanical gyroscopes, which kept improving.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The reason Honeywell, of all companies, chose to develop the laser gyro was that they were the only one that did not have a successful line of mechanical gyroscopes, so they would not be competing against themselves.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The first problem they had to solve was that with laser gyros rotations below a certain minimum could not be detected at all, due to a problem called "lock-in", whereby the two beams act like coupled oscillators and pull each other's frequencies toward convergence and therefore zero output.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The solution was to shake the gyro rapidly so that it never settled into lock-in.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Paradoxically, too regular of a dithering motion produced an accumulation of short periods of lock-in when the device was at rest at the extremities of its shaking motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This was cured by applying a random white noise to the vibration.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The material of the block was also changed from quartz to a new glass ceramic Cer-Vit, made by Owens Corning, because of helium leaks.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A fiber optic gyroscope also uses the interference of light to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The two-halves of the split beam travel in opposite directions in a coil of fiber optic cable as long as 5 km.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Like the ring laser gyroscope, it makes use of the Sagnac effect.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A London moment gyroscope relies on the quantum-mechanical phenomenon, whereby a spinning superconductor generates a magnetic field whose axis lines up exactly with the spin axis of the gyroscopic rotor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A magnetometer determines the orientation of the generated field, which is interpolated to determine the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyroscopes of this type can be extremely accurate and stable.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] For example, those used in the Gravity Probe B experiment measured changes in gyroscope spin axis orientation to better than 0.5 milliarcseconds (1.4×10−7 degrees, or about 2.4×10−9 radians) over a one-year period.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] This is equivalent to an angular separation the width of a human hair viewed from 32 kilometers (20 mi) away.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The GP-B gyro consists of a nearly-perfect spherical rotating mass made of fused quartz, which provides a dielectric support for a thin layer of niobium superconducting material.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] To eliminate friction found in conventional bearings, the rotor assembly is centered by the electric field from six electrodes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] After the initial spin-up by a jet of helium which brings the rotor to 4,000 RPM, the polished gyroscope housing is evacuated to an ultra-high vacuum to further reduce drag on the rotor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Provided the suspension electronics remain powered, the extreme rotational symmetry, lack of friction, and low drag will allow the angular momentum of the rotor to keep it spinning for about 15,000 years.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A sensitive DC SQUID that can discriminate changes as small as one quantum, or about 2 ×10−15 Wb, is used to monitor the gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A precession, or tilt, in the orientation of the rotor causes the London moment magnetic field to shift relative to the housing.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The moving field passes through a superconducting pickup loop fixed to the housing, inducing a small electric current.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The current produces a voltage across a shunt resistance, which is resolved to spherical coordinates by a microprocessor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The system is designed to minimize Lorentz torque on the rotor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The main rotor of a helicopter acts like a gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Its motion is influenced by the principle of gyroscopic precession which is the concept that a force applied to a spinning object will have a maximum reaction approximately 90 degrees later.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The reaction may differ from 90 degrees when other stronger forces are in play.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] To change direction, helicopters must adjust the pitch angle and the angle of attack.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyro X prototype vehicle created by Alex Tremulis and Thomas Summers in 1967.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The car utilized gyroscopic precession to drive on two wheels.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] An assembly consisting of a flywheel mounted in a gimbal housing under the hood of the vehicle acted as a large gyroscope.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The flywheel was rotated by hydraulic pumps creating a gyroscopic effect on the vehicle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] A precessional ram was responsible for rotating the gyroscope to change the direction of the precessional force to counteract any forces causing the vehicle imbalance.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The one-of-a-kind prototype is now at the Lane Motor Museum in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] In addition to being used in compasses, aircraft, computer pointing devices, etc., gyroscopes have been introduced into consumer electronics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Since the gyroscope allows the calculation of orientation and rotation, designers have incorporated them into modern technology.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] The integration of the gyroscope has allowed for more accurate recognition of movement within a 3D space than the previous lone accelerometer within a number of smartphones.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Gyroscopes in consumer electronics are frequently combined with accelerometers for more robust direction- and motion-sensing.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Examples of such applications include smartphones such as the Samsung Galaxy Note 4, HTC Titan, Nexus 5, iPhone 5s, Nokia 808 PureView and Sony Xperia, game console peripherals such as the PlayStation 3 controller and the Wii Remote, and virtual reality headsets such as the Oculus Rift.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Some features of Android phones like PhotoSphere or 360 Camera and to use VR gadget do not work without a gyroscope sensor in the phone.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Nintendo has integrated a gyroscope into the Wii console's Wii Remote controller by an additional piece of hardware called "Wii MotionPlus".
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] It is also included in the 3DS, Wii U GamePad, and Nintendo Switch Joy-Con and Pro controllers, which detect movement when turning and shaking.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] Cruise ships use gyroscopes to level motion-sensitive devices such as self-leveling pool tables.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/gyroscope] An electric powered flywheel gyroscope inserted in a bicycle wheel is sold as an alternative to training wheels.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] To improve their maneuverability, combat aircraft are designed to minimize moments of inertia, while civil aircraft often are not.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The **moment of inertia** (also known as **mass moment of inertia**, **angular/rotational mass**, **second moment of mass**, or **rotational inertia**) is a measure of how difficult it is to change the rotation rate of a rigid body about a given axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] It is the ratio between the torque applied and the resulting angular acceleration about that axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] It plays the same role in rotational motion as mass does in linear motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A body's moment of inertia about a particular axis depends on both the mass and its distribution relative to the axis, increasing with mass and distance from the axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For a point mass, the moment of inertia is simply the mass times the square of the perpendicular distance to the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a rigid composite system is the sum of the moments of inertia of its component subsystems (all taken about the same axis).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Its simplest definition is the second moment of mass with respect to distance from an axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If a body is forced to rotate in a plane, then only the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the plane, a scalar value, matters.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If a body is allowed to rotate in all three dimensions, then its moment is described by a symmetric 3-by-3 matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This symmetric matrix can be orthogonally diagonalized by a set of mutually perpendicular principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Torques around these principal axes act independently of each other.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] When a body is free to rotate around an axis, torque must be applied to change its angular momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The amount of torque needed to cause any given angular acceleration (the rate of change in angular velocity) is proportional to the moment of inertia of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Moments of inertia may be expressed in units of kilogram metre squared (kg·m2) in SI units and pound-foot-squared (lb·ft2) in imperial or US units.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia plays the role in rotational kinetics that mass (inertia) plays in linear kinetics—both characterize the resistance of a body to changes in its motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia depends on how mass is distributed around an axis of rotation, and will vary depending on the chosen axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For a point-like mass, the moment of inertia about some axis is given by $mr^{2}$ , where r is the distance of the point from the axis, and m is the mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For an extended rigid body, the moment of inertia is just the sum of all the small pieces of mass multiplied by the square of their distances from the axis in rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For an extended body of a regular shape and uniform density, this summation sometimes produces a simple expression that depends on the dimensions, shape and total mass of the object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] In 1673, Christiaan Huygens introduced this parameter in his study of the oscillation of a body hanging from a pivot, known as a compound pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The term *moment of inertia* ("momentum inertiae" in Latin) was introduced by Leonhard Euler in his book *Theoria motus corporum solidorum seu rigidorum* in 1765, and it is incorporated into Euler's second law.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The natural frequency of oscillation of a compound pendulum is obtained from the ratio of the torque imposed by gravity on the mass of the pendulum to the resistance to acceleration defined by the moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Comparison of this natural frequency to that of a simple pendulum consisting of a single point of mass provides a mathematical formulation for moment of inertia of an extended body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia also appears in momentum, kinetic energy, and in Newton's laws of motion for a rigid body as a physical parameter that combines its shape and mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] There is an interesting difference in the way moment of inertia appears in planar and spatial movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Planar movement has a single scalar that defines the moment of inertia, while for spatial movement the same calculations yield a 3 × 3 matrix of moments of inertia, called the inertia matrix or inertia tensor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a rotating flywheel is used in a machine to resist variations in applied torque to smooth its rotational output.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of an airplane about its longitudinal, horizontal and vertical axes determine how steering forces on the control surfaces of its wings, elevators and rudder(s) affect the plane's motions in roll, pitch and yaw.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The **moment of inertia** is defined as the product of mass of section and the square of the distance between the reference axis and the centroid of the section.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] It is denoted with the symbol *I* or *J*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If the angular momentum of a system is constant, then as the moment of inertia gets smaller, the angular velocity must increase.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This occurs when spinning figure skaters pull in their outstretched arms or divers curl their bodies into a tuck position during a dive, to spin faster.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Thus, the moment of inertia of the pendulum depends on both the mass m of a body and its geometry, or shape, as defined by the distance r to the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This simple formula generalizes to define moment of inertia for an arbitrarily shaped body as the sum of all the elemental point masses *dm* each multiplied by the square of its perpendicular distance r to an axis k.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] An arbitrary object's moment of inertia thus depends on the spatial distribution of its mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] In general, given an object of mass m, an effective radius k can be defined, dependent on a particular axis of rotation, with such a value that its moment of inertia around the axis is $I=mk^{2},$ where k is known as the radius of gyration around the axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Mathematically, the moment of inertia of a simple pendulum is the ratio of the torque due to gravity about the pivot of a pendulum to its angular acceleration about that pivot point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The force of gravity on the mass of a simple pendulum generates a torque ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {F}$ around the axis perpendicular to the plane of the pendulum movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Here $\mathbf {r}$ is the distance vector from the torque axis to the pendulum center of mass, and $\mathbf {F}$ is the net force on the mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Associated with this torque is an angular acceleration, ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ , of the string and mass around this axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Since the mass is constrained to a circle the tangential acceleration of the mass is $\mathbf {a} ={\boldsymbol {\alpha }}\times \mathbf {r}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] (The second to last step uses the vector triple product expansion with the perpendicularity of ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ and $\mathbf {r}$ .) The quantity $I=mr^{2}$ is the *moment of inertia* of this single mass around the pivot point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This shows that the quantity $I=mr^{2}$ is how mass combines with the shape of a body to define rotational inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of an arbitrarily shaped body is the sum of the values $mr^{2}$ for all of the elements of mass in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A compound pendulum is a body formed from an assembly of particles of continuous shape that rotates rigidly around a pivot.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Its moment of inertia is the sum of the moments of inertia of each of the particles that it is composed of.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Measuring this frequency of oscillation over small angular displacements provides an effective way of measuring moment of inertia of a body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A simple pendulum that has the same natural frequency as a compound pendulum defines the length L from the pivot to a point called the center of oscillation of the compound pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This point also corresponds to the center of percussion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The seconds pendulum, which provides the "tick" and "tock" of a grandfather clock, takes one second to swing from side-to-side.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This is a period of two seconds, or a natural frequency of $\pi \ \mathrm {rad/s}$ for the pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Notice that the distance to the center of oscillation of the seconds pendulum must be adjusted to accommodate different values for the local acceleration of gravity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Kater's pendulum is a compound pendulum that uses this property to measure the local acceleration of gravity, and is called a gravimeter.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a complex system such as a vehicle or airplane around its vertical axis can be measured by suspending the system from three points to form a trifilar pendulum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A trifilar pendulum is a platform supported by three wires designed to oscillate in torsion around its vertical centroidal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The period of oscillation of the trifilar pendulum yields the moment of inertia of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Moment of inertia of area is also known as the second moment of area and its physical meaning is completely different from the mass moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] These calculations are commonly used in civil engineering for structural design of beams and columns.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Cross-sectional areas calculated for vertical moment of the x-axis $I_{xx}$ and horizontal moment of the y-axis $I_{yy}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia about an axis of a body is calculated by summing $mr^{2}$ for every particle in the body, where r is the perpendicular distance to the specified axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] To see how moment of inertia arises in the study of the movement of an extended body, it is convenient to consider a rigid assembly of point masses.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Consider the kinetic energy of an assembly of N masses $m_{i}$ that lie at the distances $r_{i}$ from the pivot point P , which is the nearest point on the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Thus, moment of inertia is a physical property that combines the mass and distribution of the particles around the rotation axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Notice that rotation about different axes of the same body yield different moments of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a continuous body rotating about a specified axis is calculated in the same way, except with infinitely many point particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Here, the function $\rho$ gives the mass density at each point $(x,y,z)$ , $\mathbf {r}$ is a vector perpendicular to the axis of rotation and extending from a point on the rotation axis to a point $(x,y,z)$ in the solid, and the integration is evaluated over the volume V of the body Q .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a flat surface is similar with the mass density being replaced by its areal mass density with the integral evaluated over its area.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia of a **compound pendulum** constructed from a thin disc mounted at the end of a thin rod that oscillates around a pivot at the other end of the rod, begins with the calculation of the moment of inertia of the thin rod and thin disc about their respective centers of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A list of moments of inertia formulas for standard body shapes provides a way to obtain the moment of inertia of a complex body as an assembly of simpler shaped bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The parallel axis theorem is used to shift the reference point of the individual bodies to the reference point of the assembly.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] As one more example, consider the moment of inertia of a solid sphere of constant density about an axis through its center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This is determined by summing the moments of inertia of the thin discs that can form the sphere whose centers are along the axis chosen for consideration.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] If a mechanical system is constrained to move parallel to a fixed plane, then the rotation of a body in the system occurs around an axis $\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ perpendicular to this plane.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] In this case, the moment of inertia of the mass in this system is a scalar known as the *polar moment of inertia*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The definition of the polar moment of inertia can be obtained by considering momentum, kinetic energy and Newton's laws for the planar movement of a rigid system of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For planar movement the angular velocity vector is directed along the unit vector $\mathbf {k}$ which is perpendicular to the plane of movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] This defines the relative position vector and the velocity vector for the rigid system of the particles moving in a plane.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia $I_{\mathbf {C} }$ about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass is known as the *polar moment of inertia*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Specifically, it is the second moment of mass with respect to the orthogonal distance from an axis (or pole).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For a given amount of angular momentum, a decrease in the moment of inertia results in an increase in the angular velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Figure skaters can change their moment of inertia by pulling in their arms.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] Thus, the angular velocity achieved by a skater with outstretched arms results in a greater angular velocity when the arms are pulled in, because of the reduced moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] A figure skater is not, however, a rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] The moment of inertia $I_{\mathbf {C} }$ is the *polar moment of inertia* of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along $\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p01] where $\mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}\times \mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}=\mathbf {0}$ , and $\mathbf {\hat {e}} _{i}\times \mathbf {\hat {t}} _{i}=\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles $P_{i}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The scalar moments of inertia appear as elements in a matrix when a system of particles is assembled into a rigid body that moves in three-dimensional space.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This inertia matrix appears in the calculation of the angular momentum, kinetic energy and resultant torque of the rigid system of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let the system of n particles, $P_{i},i=1,\dots ,n$ be located at the coordinates $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ with velocities $\mathbf {v} _{i}$ relative to a fixed reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The kinetic energy of a rigid system of particles can be formulated in terms of the center of mass and a matrix of mass moments of inertia of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Since the center of mass is defined by $\sum _{i=1}^{n}m_{i}\Delta \mathbf {r} _{i}=0$ , the second term in this equation is zero.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The inertia matrix appears in the application of Newton's second law to a rigid assembly of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The resultant torque on this system is, ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\sum _{i=1}^{n}\left(\mathbf {r_{i}} -\mathbf {R} \right)\times m_{i}\mathbf {a} _{i},$ where $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ is the acceleration of the particle $P_{i}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The inertia matrix of a body depends on the choice of the reference point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] There is a useful relationship between the inertia matrix relative to the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ and the inertia matrix relative to another point $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This relationship is called the parallel axis theorem.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let $\mathbf {C}$ be the center of mass of the rigid system, then $\mathbf {R} =(\mathbf {R} -\mathbf {C} )+\mathbf {C} =\mathbf {d} +\mathbf {C} ,$ where $\mathbf {d}$ is the vector from the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ to the reference point $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The first term is the inertia matrix $\mathbf {I_{C}}$ relative to the center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The second and third terms are zero by definition of the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] And the last term is the total mass of the system multiplied by the square of the skew-symmetric matrix $[\mathbf {d} ]$ constructed from $\mathbf {d}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The result is the parallel axis theorem, $\mathbf {I} _{\mathbf {R} }=\mathbf {I} _{\mathbf {C} }-M[\mathbf {d} ]^{2},$ where $\mathbf {d}$ is the vector from the center of mass $\mathbf {C}$ to the reference point $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let a rigid assembly of n particles, $P_{i},i=1,\dots ,n$ , have coordinates $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Choose $\mathbf {R}$ as a reference point and compute the moment of inertia around a line L defined by the unit vector $\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ through the reference point $\mathbf {R}$ , $\mathbf {L} (t)=\mathbf {R} +t\mathbf {\hat {k}}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This shows that the inertia matrix can be used to calculate the moment of inertia of a body around any specified rotation axis in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] For the same object, different axes of rotation will have different moments of inertia about those axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] In general, the moments of inertia are not equal unless the object is symmetric about all axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The **moment of inertia tensor** is a convenient way to summarize all moments of inertia of an object with one quantity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] It may be calculated with respect to any point in space, although for practical purposes the center of mass is most commonly used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Note that, by the definition, $\mathbf {I}$ is a symmetric tensor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Here $I_{xx}$ denotes the moment of inertia around the x -axis when the objects are rotated around the x-axis, $I_{xy}$ denotes the moment of inertia around the y -axis when the objects are rotated around the x -axis, and so on.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] These quantities can be generalized to an object with distributed mass, described by a mass density function, in a similar fashion to the scalar moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] A product of inertia term such as $I_{12}$ is obtained by the computation $I_{12}=\mathbf {e} _{1}\cdot \mathbf {I} \cdot \mathbf {e} _{2},$ and can be interpreted as the moment of inertia around the x -axis when the object rotates around the y -axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The components of tensors of degree two can be assembled into a matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] It is common in rigid body mechanics to use notation that explicitly identifies the x , y , and z -axes, such as $I_{xx}$ and $I_{xy}$ , for the components of the inertia tensor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] There are some CAD and CAE applications such as SolidWorks, Unigraphics NX/Siemens NX and MSC Adams that use an alternate convention for the products of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If one has the inertia data $(I_{xx},I_{yy},I_{zz},I_{xy},I_{xz},I_{yz})$ without knowing which inertia convention that has been used, it can be determined if one also has the principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Next, one calculates the eigenvectors for the two matrices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The matrix whose eigenvectors are parallel to the principal axes corresponds to the inertia convention that has been used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The distance r of a particle at $\mathbf {x}$ from the axis of rotation passing through the origin in the $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ direction is $\left|\mathbf {x} -\left(\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {\hat {n}} \right)\mathbf {\hat {n}} \right|$ , where $\mathbf {\hat {n}}$ is a unit vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] For multiple particles, we need only recall that the moment of inertia is additive in order to see that this formula is correct.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let $\mathbf {I} _{0}$ be the inertia tensor of a body calculated at its center of mass, and $\mathbf {R}$ be the displacement vector of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let $\mathbf {R}$ be the matrix that represents a body's rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The use of the inertia matrix in Newton's second law assumes its components are computed relative to axes parallel to the inertial frame and not relative to a body-fixed reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] This means that as the body moves the components of the inertia matrix change with time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] In contrast, the components of the inertia matrix measured in a body-fixed frame are constant.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Notice that $\mathbf {A}$ changes as the body moves, while $\mathbf {I} _{\mathbf {C} }^{B}$ remains constant.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Measured in the body frame, the inertia matrix is a constant real symmetric matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The columns of the rotation matrix $\mathbf {Q}$ define the directions of the principal axes of the body, and the constants $I_{1}$ , $I_{2}$ , and $I_{3}$ are called the **principal moments of inertia**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Sylvester (1852), and is a form of Sylvester's law of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] When the body has an axis of symmetry (sometimes called the **figure axis** or **axis of figure**) then the other two moments of inertia will be identical and any axis perpendicular to the axis of symmetry will be a principal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] A toy top is an example of a rotating rigid body, and the word *top* is used in the names of types of rigid bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] When all principal moments of inertia are distinct, the principal axes through center of mass are uniquely specified and the rigid body is called an **asymmetric top**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If two principal moments are the same, the rigid body is called a **symmetric top** and there is no unique choice for the two corresponding principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If all three principal moments are the same, the rigid body is called a **spherical top** (although it need not be spherical) and any axis can be considered a principal axis, meaning that the moment of inertia is the same about any axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The principal axes are often aligned with the object's symmetry axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If a rigid body has an axis of symmetry of order m , meaning it is symmetrical under rotations of 360°/*m* about the given axis, that axis is a principal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] When $m>2$ , the rigid body is a symmetric top.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If a rigid body has at least two symmetry axes that are not parallel or perpendicular to each other, it is a spherical top, for example, a cube or any other Platonic solid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The motion of vehicles is often described in terms of yaw, pitch, and roll which usually correspond approximately to rotations about the three principal axes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] If the vehicle has bilateral symmetry then one of the principal axes will correspond exactly to the transverse (pitch) axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] A practical example of this mathematical phenomenon is the routine automotive task of balancing a tire, which basically means adjusting the distribution of mass of a car wheel such that its principal axis of inertia is aligned with the axle so the wheel does not wobble.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Rotating molecules are also classified as asymmetric, symmetric, or spherical tops, and the structure of their rotational spectra is different for each type.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] The moment of inertia matrix in body-frame coordinates is a quadratic form that defines a surface in the body called Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let ${\boldsymbol {\Lambda }}$ be the inertia matrix relative to the center of mass aligned with the principal axes, then the surface $\mathbf {x} ^{\mathsf {T}}{\boldsymbol {\Lambda }}\mathbf {x} =1,$ or $I_{1}x^{2}+I_{2}y^{2}+I_{3}z^{2}=1,$ defines an ellipsoid in the body frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/moment-of-inertia-p02] Let a point $\mathbf {x}$ on this ellipsoid be defined in terms of its magnitude and direction, $\mathbf {x} =\|\mathbf {x} \|\mathbf {n}$ , where $\mathbf {n}$ is a unit vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In astronomy, **precession** refers to any of several slow changes in an astronomical body's rotational or orbital parameters.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] An important example is the steady change in the orientation of the axis of rotation of the Earth, known as the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Torque-free precession implies that no external moment (torque) is applied to the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In torque-free precession, the angular momentum is a constant, but the angular velocity vector changes orientation with time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] What makes this possible is a time-varying moment of inertia, or more precisely, a time-varying inertia matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The inertia matrix is composed of the moments of inertia of a body calculated with respect to separate coordinate axes (e.g.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] If an object is asymmetric about its principal axis of rotation, the moment of inertia with respect to each coordinate direction will change with time, while preserving angular momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The result is that the component of the angular velocities of the body about each axis will vary inversely with each axis' moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] When an object is not perfectly rigid, inelastic dissipation will tend to damp torque-free precession, and the rotation axis will align itself with one of the inertia axes of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] For a generic solid object without any axis of symmetry, the evolution of the object's orientation, represented (for example) by a rotation matrix **R** that transforms internal to external coordinates, may be numerically simulated.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Torque-induced precession (**gyroscopic precession**) is the phenomenon in which the axis of a spinning object (e.g., a gyroscope) describes a cone in space when an external torque is applied to it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The phenomenon is commonly seen in a spinning toy top, but all rotating objects can undergo precession.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] If the speed of the rotation and the magnitude of the external torque are constant, the spin axis will move at right angles to the direction that would intuitively result from the external torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In the case of a toy top, its weight is acting downwards from its center of mass and the normal force (reaction) of the ground is pushing up on it at the point of contact with the support.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] These two opposite forces produce a torque which causes the top to precess.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The device depicted on the right is gimbal-mounted.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] From inside to outside there are three axes of rotation: the hub of the wheel, the gimbal axis, and the vertical pivot.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] To distinguish between the two horizontal axes, rotation around the wheel hub will be called *spinning*, and rotation around the gimbal axis will be called *pitching*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Rotation around the vertical pivot axis is called *rotation*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] First, imagine that the entire device is rotating around the (vertical) pivot axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Then, spinning of the wheel (around the wheelhub) is added.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Imagine the gimbal axis to be locked, so that the wheel cannot pitch.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The gimbal axis has sensors, that measure whether there is a torque around the gimbal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In the picture, a section of the wheel has been named *dm*1.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] At the depicted moment in time, section *dm*1 is at the perimeter of the rotating motion around the (vertical) pivot axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Section *dm*2 of the wheel is moving away from the pivot axis, and so a force (again, a Coriolis force) acts in the same direction as in the case of *dm*1.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Note that both arrows point in the same direction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The same reasoning applies for the bottom half of the wheel, but there the arrows point in the opposite direction to that of the top arrows.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Combined over the entire wheel, there is a torque around the gimbal axis when some spinning is added to rotation around a vertical axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The torque around the gimbal axis arises without any delay; the response is instantaneous.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In the discussion above, the setup was kept unchanging by preventing pitching around the gimbal axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In the case of a spinning toy top, when the spinning top starts tilting, gravity exerts a torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] However, instead of rolling over, the spinning top just pitches a little.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] This pitching motion reorients the spinning top with respect to the torque that is being exerted.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The result is that the torque exerted by gravity – via the pitching motion – elicits gyroscopic precession (which in turn yields a counter torque against the gravity torque) rather than causing the spinning top to fall to its side.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Precession or gyroscopic considerations have an effect on bicycle performance at high speed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Precession is also the mechanism behind gyrocompasses.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Precession is the change of angular velocity and angular momentum produced by a torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The general equation that relates the torque to the rate of change of angular momentum is: ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {L} }{\mathrm {d} t}}$ where ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}$ and $\mathbf {L}$ are the torque and angular momentum vectors respectively.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Due to the way the torque vectors are defined, it is a vector that is perpendicular to the plane of the forces that create it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Thus it may be seen that the angular momentum vector will change perpendicular to those forces.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Depending on how the forces are created, they will often rotate with the angular momentum vector, and then circular precession is created.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] where *I*s is the moment of inertia, ***ω***s is the angular velocity of spin about the spin axis, m is the mass, *g* is the acceleration due to gravity, θ is the angle between the spin axis and the axis of precession and *r* is the distance between the center of mass and the pivot.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The torque vector originates at the center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Where *I*s is the moment of inertia, *T*s is the period of spin about the spin axis, and **τ** is the torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In general, the problem is more complicated than this, however.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The special and general theories of relativity give three types of corrections to the Newtonian precession, of a gyroscope near a large mass such as Earth, described above.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The Schwarzschild geodesics (sometimes Schwarzschild precession) are used in the prediction of the anomalous perihelion precession of the planets, most notably for the accurate prediction of the apsidal precession of Mercury.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In astronomy, precession refers to any of several gravity-induced, slow and continuous changes in an astronomical body's rotational axis or orbital path.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Precession of the equinoxes, perihelion precession, changes in the tilt of Earth's axis to its orbit, and the eccentricity of its orbit over tens of thousands of years are all important parts of the astronomical theory of ice ages.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Axial precession is the movement of the rotational axis of an astronomical body, whereby the axis slowly traces out a cone.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In the case of Earth, this type of precession is also known as the *precession of the equinoxes*, *lunisolar precession*, or *precession of the equator*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Earth goes through one such complete precessional cycle in a period of approximately 26,000 years or 1° every 72 years, during which the positions of stars will slowly change in both equatorial coordinates and ecliptic longitude.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Over this cycle, Earth's north axial pole moves from where it is now, within 1° of Polaris, in a circle around the ecliptic pole, with an angular radius of about 23.5°.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The ancient Greek astronomer Hipparchus (c.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] 190–120 BC) is generally accepted to be the earliest known astronomer to recognize and assess the precession of the equinoxes at about 1° per century (which is not far from the actual value for antiquity, 1.38°), although there is some minor dispute about whether he was.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In ancient China, the Jin dynasty scholar-official Yu Xi (fl.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] 307–345 AD) made a similar discovery centuries later, noting that the position of the Sun during the winter solstice had drifted roughly one degree over the course of fifty years relative to the position of the stars.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The precession of Earth's axis was later explained by Newtonian physics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Being an oblate spheroid, Earth has a non-spherical shape, bulging outward at the equator.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The gravitational tidal forces of the Moon and Sun apply torque to the equator, attempting to pull the equatorial bulge into the plane of the ecliptic, but instead causing it to precess.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The torque exerted by the planets, particularly Jupiter, also plays a role.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Precessional movement of the axis (left), precession of the equinox in relation to the distant stars (middle), and the path of the north celestial pole among the stars due to the precession.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Vega is the bright star near the bottom (right).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] This is called perihelion precession or apsidal precession.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] In the adjunct image, Earth's apsidal precession is illustrated.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] As the Earth travels around the Sun, its elliptical orbit rotates gradually over time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] The eccentricity of its ellipse and the precession rate of its orbit are exaggerated for visualization.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Most orbits in the Solar System have a much smaller eccentricity and precess at a much slower rate, making them nearly circular and nearly stationary.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/precession] Deviating from Newton's law, Einstein's theory of gravitation predicts an extra term of ⁠*A*/*r*4⁠, which accurately gives the observed excess turning rate of 43 arcseconds per century.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In classical mechanics, **rigid body dynamics** studies the movement of systems of interconnected bodies under the action of external forces.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Along with statics, it forms the field of **rigid body mechanics**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The assumption that the bodies are *rigid* (i.e. they do not deform under the action of applied forces) simplifies analysis, by reducing the parameters that describe the configuration of the system to the translation and rotation of body-fixed frames.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This excludes bodies that display fluid, highly elastic, and plastic behavior.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of a rigid body system is described by the laws of kinematics and by the application of Newton's second law (kinetics) or their derivative form, Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution of these equations of motion provides a description of the position, the motion and the acceleration of the individual components of the system, and overall the system itself, as a function of time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The formulation and solution of rigid body dynamics is an important tool in the computer simulation of mechanical systems.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of particles moves parallel to a fixed plane, the system is said to be constrained to planar movement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, Newton's laws (kinetics) for a rigid system of N particles, P*i*, *i*=1,...,*N*, simplify because there is no movement in the *k* direction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where **r**i denotes the planar trajectory of each particle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] For systems that are constrained to planar movement, the angular velocity and angular acceleration vectors are directed along **k** perpendicular to the plane of movement, which simplifies this acceleration equation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {e} _{i}=0}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {e} _{i}\times \mathbf {t} _{i}=\mathbf {k} }$ is the unit vector perpendicular to the plane for all of the particles Pi.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where M is the total mass and *I***C** is the moment of inertia about an axis perpendicular to the movement of the rigid system and through the center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Several methods to describe orientations of a rigid body in three dimensions have been developed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are summarized in the following sections.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The first attempt to represent an orientation is attributed to Leonhard Euler.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The values of these three rotations are called Euler angles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Commonly, $\psi$ is used to denote precession, $\theta$ nutation, and $\phi$ intrinsic rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These are three angles, also known as yaw, pitch and roll, Navigation angles and Cardan angles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Mathematically they constitute a set of six possibilities inside the twelve possible sets of Euler angles, the ordering being the one best used for describing the orientation of a vehicle such as an airplane.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In aerospace engineering they are usually referred to as Euler angles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Euler also realized that the composition of two rotations is equivalent to a single rotation about a different fixed axis (Euler's rotation theorem).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, the composition of the former three angles has to be equal to only one rotation, whose axis was complicated to calculate until matrices were developed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Based on this fact he introduced a vectorial way to describe any rotation, with a vector on the rotation axis and module equal to the value of the angle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, any orientation can be represented by a rotation vector (also called Euler vector) that leads to it from the reference frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, the rotation vector is commonly called orientation vector, or attitude vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A similar method, called axis-angle representation, describes a rotation or orientation using a unit vector aligned with the rotation axis, and a separate value to indicate the angle (see figure).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With the introduction of matrices the Euler theorems were rewritten.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The rotations were described by orthogonal matrices referred to as rotation matrices or direction cosine matrices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent an orientation, a rotation matrix is commonly called orientation matrix, or attitude matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The above-mentioned Euler vector is the eigenvector of a rotation matrix (a rotation matrix has a unique real eigenvalue).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The product of two rotation matrices is the composition of rotations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Therefore, as before, the orientation can be given as the rotation from the initial frame to achieve the frame that we want to describe.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The configuration space of a non-symmetrical object in *n*-dimensional space is SO(*n*) × **R***n*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Orientation may be visualized by attaching a basis of tangent vectors to an object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The direction in which each vector points determines its orientation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Another way to describe rotations is using rotation quaternions, also called versors.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] They are equivalent to rotation matrices and rotation vectors.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] With respect to rotation vectors, they can be more easily converted to and from matrices.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] When used to represent orientations, rotation quaternions are typically called orientation quaternions or attitude quaternions.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To consider rigid body dynamics in three-dimensional space, Newton's second law must be extended to define the relationship between the movement of a rigid body and the system of forces and torques that act on it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The extension of Newton's second law to rigid bodies is achieved by considering a rigid system of particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] If a system of *N* particles, Pi, i=1,...,*N*, are assembled into a rigid body, then Newton's second law can be applied to each of the particles in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An important simplification to these force equations is obtained by introducing the resultant force and torque that acts on the rigid system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This resultant force and torque is obtained by choosing one of the particles in the system as a reference point, **R**, where each of the external forces are applied with the addition of an associated torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The resultant force **F** and torque **T** are given by the formulas, $\mathbf {F} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}\mathbf {F} _{i},\quad \mathbf {T} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}(\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )\times \mathbf {F} _{i},$ where **R**i is the vector that defines the position of particle Pi.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The mass properties of the rigid body are represented by its center of mass and inertia matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] then it is known as the center of mass of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] where $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the column vector **R**i − **R**; $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is its transpose, and $\mathbf {I}$ is the 3 by 3 identity matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] $\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}\mathbf {S} _{i}$ is the scalar product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself, while $\mathbf {S} _{i}\mathbf {S} _{i}^{\textsf {T}}$ is the tensor product of $\mathbf {S} _{i}$ with itself.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Using the center of mass and inertia matrix, the force and torque equations for a single rigid body take the form $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a} ,\quad \mathbf {T} =[I_{R}]\alpha +\omega \times [I_{R}]\omega ,$ and are known as Newton's second law of motion for a rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The dynamics of an interconnected system of rigid bodies, *B**i*, *j* = 1, ..., *M*, is formulated by isolating each rigid body and introducing the interaction forces.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Newton's formulation yields 6*M* equations that define the dynamics of a system of *M* rigid bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] A rotating object, whether under the influence of torques or not, may exhibit the behaviours of precession and nutation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The solution to this equation when there is no applied torque is discussed in the articles Euler's equation of motion and Poinsot's ellipsoid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It follows from Euler's equation that a torque **τ** applied perpendicular to the axis of rotation, and therefore perpendicular to **L**, results in a rotation about an axis perpendicular to both **τ** and **L**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Precession can be demonstrated by placing a spinning top with its axis horizontal and supported loosely (frictionless toward precession) at one end.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Instead of falling, as might be expected, the top appears to defy gravity by remaining with its axis horizontal, when the other end of the axis is left unsupported and the free end of the axis slowly describes a circle in a horizontal plane, the resulting precession turning.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This effect is explained by the above equations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The torque on the top is supplied by a couple of forces: gravity acting downward on the device's centre of mass, and an equal force acting upward to support one end of the device.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Under a constant torque of magnitude *τ*, the speed of precession *Ω*P is inversely proportional to *L*, the magnitude of its angular momentum: $\tau ={\mathit {\Omega }}_{\mathrm {P} }L\sin \theta ,$ where *θ* is the angle between the vectors **Ω**P and **L**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, if the top's spin slows down (for example, due to friction), its angular momentum decreases and so the rate of precession increases.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This continues until the device is unable to rotate fast enough to support its own weight, when it stops precessing and falls off its support, mostly because friction against precession cause another precession that goes to cause the fall.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] By convention, these three vectors – torque, spin, and precession – are all oriented with respect to each other according to the right-hand rule.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] An alternate formulation of rigid body dynamics that has a number of convenient features is obtained by considering the virtual work of forces acting on a rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The virtual work of forces acting at various points on a single rigid body can be calculated using the velocities of their point of application and the resultant force and torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The trajectories of **R***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n* are defined by the movement of the rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The velocity of the points **R***i* along their trajectories are $\mathbf {V} _{i}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times (\mathbf {R} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where **ω** is the angular velocity vector of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] is known as the generalized force associated with the virtual displacement δq.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] It is useful to note that conservative forces such as gravity and spring forces are derivable from a potential function *V*(*q*1, ..., *q**n*), known as a potential energy.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The equations of motion for a mechanical system of rigid bodies can be determined using D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The principle of virtual work is used to study the static equilibrium of a system of rigid bodies; however, by introducing acceleration terms in Newton's laws this approach is generalized to define dynamic equilibrium.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The static equilibrium of a mechanical system rigid bodies is defined by the condition that the virtual work of the applied forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] This is known as the *principle of virtual work.* This is equivalent to the requirement that the generalized forces for any virtual displacement are zero, that is *Q**i*=0.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let a mechanical system be constructed from n rigid bodies, B*i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, and let the resultant of the applied forces on each body be the force-torque pairs, **F***i* and **T***i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Notice that these applied forces do not include the reaction forces where the bodies are connected.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Finally, assume that the velocity **V***i* and angular velocities ***ω****i*, *i* = 1, ..., *n*, for each rigid body, are defined by a single generalized coordinate q.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Such a system of rigid bodies is said to have one degree of freedom.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] These m equations define the static equilibrium of the system of rigid bodies.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Consider a single rigid body which moves under the action of a resultant force **F** and torque **T**, with one degree of freedom defined by the generalized coordinate *q*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] D'Alembert's form of the principle of virtual work states that a system of rigid bodies is in dynamic equilibrium when the virtual work of the sum of the applied forces and the inertial forces is zero for any virtual displacement of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Thus, dynamic equilibrium of a system of n rigid bodies with m generalized coordinates requires that $\delta W=\left(Q_{1}+Q_{1}^{*}\right)\delta q_{1}+\dots +\left(Q_{m}+Q_{m}^{*}\right)\delta q_{m}=0,$ for any set of virtual displacements *δq**j*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] In this case, introduce the Lagrangian, *L* = *T* − *V*, so these equations of motion become ${\frac {d}{dt}}{\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}_{j}}}-{\frac {\partial L}{\partial q_{j}}}=0\quad j=1,\ldots ,m.$ These are known as Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] The linear and angular momentum of a rigid system of particles is formulated by measuring the position and velocity of the particles relative to the center of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Let the system of particles Pi, *i* = 1, ..., *n* be located at the coordinates **r***i* and velocities **v***i*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] To specialize these formulas to a rigid body, assume the particles are rigidly connected to each other so Pi, i=1,...,n are located by the coordinates **r**i and velocities **v**i.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body-dynamics] Select a reference point **R** and compute the relative position and velocity vectors, $\mathbf {r} _{i}=(\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {R} ,\quad \mathbf {v} _{i}=\omega \times (\mathbf {r} _{i}-\mathbf {R} )+\mathbf {V} ,$ where ω is the angular velocity of the system.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In classical mechanics, a **rigid body**, also known as a **rigid object**, is a solid body in which deformation is zero or negligible, when a deforming pressure or deforming force is applied on it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The distance between any two given points on a rigid body remains constant in time regardless of external forces or moments exerted on it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] A rigid body is usually considered as a continuous distribution of mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] *Mechanics of rigid bodies* is a field within mechanics where motions and forces of objects are studied without considering effects that can cause deformation (as opposed to mechanics of materials, where deformable objects are considered).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In the study of special relativity, a perfectly rigid body does not exist; and objects can only be assumed to be rigid if they are not moving near the speed of light, where the mass is infinitely large.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In quantum mechanics, a rigid body is usually thought of as a collection of point masses.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] For instance, molecules (consisting of the point masses: electrons and nuclei) are often seen as rigid bodies (see classification of molecules as rigid rotors).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The position of a rigid body is the position of all the particles of which it is composed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] To simplify the description of this position, we exploit the property that the body is rigid, namely that all its particles maintain the same distance relative to each other.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] If the body is rigid, it is sufficient to describe the position of at least three non-collinear particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] This makes it possible to reconstruct the position of all the other particles, provided that their time-invariant position relative to the three selected particles is known.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] However, typically a different, mathematically more convenient, but equivalent approach is used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] 2. the *angular position* (also known as *orientation*, or *attitude*) of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Thus, the position of a rigid body has two components: *linear* and *angular*, respectively.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The same is true for other kinematic and kinetic quantities describing the motion of a rigid body, such as linear and angular velocity, acceleration, momentum, impulse, and kinetic energy.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The linear position can be represented by a vector with its tail at an arbitrary reference point in space (the origin of a chosen coordinate system) and its tip at an arbitrary point of interest on the rigid body, typically coinciding with its center of mass or centroid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] This reference point may define the origin of a coordinate system fixed to the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] There are several ways to numerically describe the orientation of a rigid body, including a set of three Euler angles, a quaternion, or a direction cosine matrix (also referred to as a rotation matrix).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] All these methods actually define the orientation of a basis set (or coordinate system) which has a fixed orientation relative to the body (i.e. rotates together with the body), relative to another basis set (or coordinate system), from which the motion of the rigid body is observed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In general, when a rigid body moves, both its position and orientation vary with time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In the kinematic sense, these changes are referred to as *translation* and *rotation*, respectively.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Indeed, the position of a rigid body can be viewed as a hypothetic translation and rotation (roto-translation) of the body starting from a hypothetic reference position (not necessarily coinciding with a position actually taken by the body during its motion).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The linear velocity of a rigid body is a vector quantity, equal to the time rate of change of its linear position.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Thus, it is the velocity of a reference point fixed to the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] During purely translational motion (motion with no rotation), all points on a rigid body move with the same velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] However, when motion involves rotation, the instantaneous velocity of any two points on the body will generally not be the same.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Two points of a rotating body will have the same instantaneous velocity only if they happen to lie on an axis parallel to the instantaneous axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In this case, rigid bodies and reference frames are indistinguishable and completely interchangeable.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The norm of a position vector is the spatial distance.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Here the coordinates of all three vectors must be expressed in coordinate frames with the same orientation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] where O is any arbitrary point fixed in reference frame N, and the N to the left of the d/d*t* operator indicates that the derivative is taken in reference frame N.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The result is independent of the selection of O so long as O is fixed in N.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] where $\mathbf {r} ^{\mathrm {PQ} }$ is the position vector from P to Q., with coordinates expressed in N (or a frame with the same orientation as N.) This relation can be derived from the temporal invariance of the norm distance between P and Q.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] where $\scriptstyle {{}^{\mathrm {N} }\!{\boldsymbol {\alpha }}^{\mathrm {B} }}$ is the angular acceleration of B in the reference frame N.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] where Q is the point fixed in B that is instantaneously coincident with R at the instant of interest.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] This relation is often combined with the relation for the **Velocity of two points fixed on a rigid body**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] where Q is the point fixed in B that instantaneously coincident with R at the instant of interest.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] This equation is often combined with **Acceleration of two points fixed on a rigid body**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In 2D, the angular velocity is a scalar, and matrix A(t) simply represents a rotation in the *xy*-plane by an angle which is the integral of the angular velocity over time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Vehicles, walking people, etc., usually rotate according to changes in the direction of the velocity: they move forward with respect to their own orientation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Then, if the body follows a closed orbit in a plane, the angular velocity integrated over a time interval in which the orbit is completed once, is an integer times 360°.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] This integer is the winding number with respect to the origin of the velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Compare the amount of rotation associated with the vertices of a polygon.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Assume that $\mathbf {v} (\mathbf {P} )$ is a smooth 3-d vector field and O is a point in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , with $\mathbf {v} _{O}=\mathbf {v} (O)$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Denote $B_{\varepsilon }$ the ball of radius $\varepsilon$ centered at O , and $\mathbf {r} =\mathbf {P} -O$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Linearizing the velocity field at O gives $\mathbf {v} (\mathbf {P} )-\mathbf {v} _{O}=(\nabla \mathbf {v} )_{O}\,\mathbf {r} +o(r),$ where $(\nabla \mathbf {v} )_{O}$ is the Jacobian matrix at O .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Decompose it into symmetric and antisymmetric parts: $(\nabla \mathbf {v} )_{O}=J_{s}+J_{a}$ , with $J_{a}$ antisymmetric.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] By linear algebra, there exists a vector ${\boldsymbol {w}}$ such that $J_{a}\mathbf {r} ={\boldsymbol {w}}\times \mathbf {r}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In fact, direct computation shows that ${\boldsymbol {w}}={1 \over 2}\nabla \times \mathbf {v} (O)$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Now, assume a rigid body is rotating with angular velocity ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Thus ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}={\boldsymbol {w}}$ and the terms $o(r)$ and $o(\varepsilon ^{3})$ vanish identically in the above formulae.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Any point that is rigidly connected to the body can be used as reference point (origin of coordinate system *L*) to describe the linear motion of the body (the linear position, velocity and acceleration vectors depend on the choice).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Two rigid bodies are said to be different (not copies) if there is no proper rotation from one to the other.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] A rigid body is called chiral if its mirror image is different in that sense, i.e., if it has either no symmetry or its symmetry group contains only proper rotations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] In the opposite case an object is called achiral: the mirror image is a copy, not a different object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] Such an object may have a symmetry plane, but not necessarily: there may also be a plane of reflection with respect to which the image of the object is a rotated version.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The latter applies for *S2n*, of which the case *n* = 1 is inversion symmetry.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] For a (rigid) rectangular transparent sheet, inversion symmetry corresponds to having on one side an image without rotational symmetry and on the other side an image such that what shines through is the image at the top side, upside down.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] A sheet with a through and through image is achiral.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The configuration space of a rigid body with one point fixed (i.e., a body with zero translational motion) is given by the underlying manifold of the rotation group SO(3).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rigid-body] The configuration space of a nonfixed (with non-zero translational motion) rigid body is *E*+(3), the subgroup of direct isometries of the Euclidean group in three dimensions (combinations of translations and rotations).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] This concept assumes that the rotation is also stable, such that no torque is required to keep it going.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The kinematics and dynamics of rotation around a fixed axis of a rigid body are mathematically much simpler than those for free rotation of a rigid body; they are entirely analogous to those of linear motion along a single fixed direction, which is not true for *free rotation of a rigid body*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The expressions for the kinetic energy of the object, and for the forces on the parts of the object, are also simpler for rotation around a fixed axis, than for general rotational motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] For these reasons, rotation around a fixed axis is typically taught in introductory physics courses after students have mastered linear motion; the full generality of rotational motion is not usually taught in introductory physics classes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A *rigid body* is an object of a finite extent in which all the distances between the component particles are constant.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] No truly rigid body exists; external forces can deform any solid.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] For our purposes, then, a rigid body is a solid which requires large forces to deform it appreciably.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A change in the position of a particle in three-dimensional space can be completely specified by three coordinates.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A change in the position of a rigid body is more complicated to describe.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] It can be regarded as a combination of two distinct types of motion: translational motion and circular motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Purely *translational motion* occurs when every particle of the body has the same instantaneous velocity as every other particle; then the path traced out by any particle is exactly parallel to the path traced out by every other particle in the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Under translational motion, the change in the position of a rigid body is specified completely by three coordinates such as *x*, *y*, and *z* giving the displacement of any point, such as the center of mass, fixed to the rigid body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Purely *rotational motion* occurs if every particle in the body moves in a circle about a single line.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] This line is called the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Then the radius vectors from the axis to all particles undergo the same angular displacement at the same time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The axis of rotation need not go through the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In general, any rotation can be specified completely by the three angular displacements with respect to the rectangular-coordinate axes *x*, *y*, and *z*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Any change in the position of the rigid body is thus completely described by three translational and three rotational coordinates.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Any displacement of a rigid body may be arrived at by first subjecting the body to a displacement followed by a rotation, or conversely, to a rotation followed by a displacement.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] There remains the matter of describing the rotation of the body about the center of mass and relating it to the external forces acting on the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The kinematics and dynamics of *rotational motion around a single axis* resemble the kinematics and dynamics of translational motion; rotational motion around a single axis even has a work-energy theorem analogous to that of particle dynamics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Given a particle that moves along the circumference of a circle of radius r , having moved an arc length s , its angular position is $\theta$ relative to its initial position, where $\theta ={\frac {s}{r}}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In mathematics and physics it is conventional to treat the radian, a unit of plane angle, as 1, often omitting it.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] An angular displacement is a change in angular position: $\Delta \theta =\theta _{2}-\theta _{1},$ where $\Delta \theta$ is the angular displacement, $\theta _{1}$ is the initial angular position and $\theta _{2}$ is the final angular position.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Change in angular displacement per unit time is called angular velocity with direction along the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The symbol for angular velocity is $\omega$ and the units are typically rad s−1.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Using the formula for angular position and letting $v={\frac {ds}{dt}}$ , we have also $\omega ={\frac {d\theta }{dt}}={\frac {v}{r}},$ where v is the translational speed of the particle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A changing angular velocity indicates the presence of an angular acceleration in rigid body, typically measured in rad s−2.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Thus, the angular acceleration is the rate of change of the angular velocity, just as acceleration is the rate of change of velocity.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The translational acceleration of a point on the object rotating is given by $a=r\alpha ,$ where *r* is the radius or distance from the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] This is also the tangential component of acceleration: it is tangential to the direction of motion of the point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] If this component is 0, the motion is uniform circular motion, and the velocity changes in direction only.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The radial acceleration (perpendicular to direction of motion) is given by $a_{\mathrm {R} }={\frac {v^{2}}{r}}=\omega ^{2}r\,.$ It is directed towards the center of the rotational motion, and is often called the *centripetal acceleration*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The angular acceleration is caused by the torque, which can have a positive or negative value in accordance with the convention of positive and negative angular frequency.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The relationship between torque and angular acceleration (how difficult it is to start, stop, or otherwise change rotation) is given by the moment of inertia: ${\displaystyle {\boldsymbol {\tau }}}=I\alpha$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The moment of inertia of an object, symbolized by I , is a measure of the object's resistance to changes to its rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The moment of inertia is measured in kilogram metre² (kg m2).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] It depends on the object's mass: increasing the mass of an object increases the moment of inertia.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] It also depends on the distribution of the mass: distributing the mass further from the center of rotation increases the moment of inertia by a greater degree.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Torque ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}$ is the twisting effect of a force **F** applied to a rotating object which is at position **r** from its axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Mathematically, ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {F} ,$ where × denotes the cross product.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A net torque acting upon an object will produce an angular acceleration of the object according to ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=I{\boldsymbol {\alpha }},$ just as **F** = *m***a** in linear dynamics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The angular momentum $\mathbf {L}$ is a measure of the difficulty of bringing a rotating object to rest.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] It is given by $\mathbf {L} =\sum \mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p} ,$ where the sum is taken over all particles in the object.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Angular momentum is the product of moment of inertia and angular velocity: $\mathbf {L} =I{\boldsymbol {\omega }},$ just as **p** = *m***v** in linear dynamics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The analog of linear momentum in rotational motion is angular momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The greater the angular momentum of the spinning object such as a top, the greater its tendency to continue to spin.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The angular momentum of a rotating body is proportional to its mass and to how rapidly it is turning.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In addition, the angular momentum depends on how the mass is distributed relative to the axis of rotation: the further away the mass is located from the axis of rotation, the greater the angular momentum.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A flat disk such as a record turntable has less angular momentum than a hollow cylinder of the same mass and velocity of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Like linear momentum, angular momentum is vector quantity, and its conservation implies that the direction of the spin axis tends to remain unchanged.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] For this reason, the spinning top remains upright whereas a stationary one falls over immediately.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The angular momentum equation can be used to relate the moment of the resultant force on a body about an axis (sometimes called torque), and the rate of rotation about that axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Torque and angular momentum are related according to ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}={\frac {d\mathbf {L} }{dt}},$ just as **F** = *d***p**/*dt* in linear dynamics.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In the absence of an external torque, the angular momentum of a body remains constant.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The conservation of angular momentum is notably demonstrated in figure skating: when pulling the arms closer to the body during a spin, the moment of inertia is decreased, and so the angular velocity is increased.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The amount of translational kinetic energy found in two variables: the mass of the object ( m ) and the speed of the object ( v ) as shown in the equation above.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Kinetic energy must always be either zero or a positive value.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] While velocity can have either a positive or negative value, velocity squared will always be positive.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The above development is a special case of general rotational motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In the general case, angular displacement, angular velocity, angular acceleration, and torque are considered to be vectors.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] An angular displacement is considered to be a vector, pointing along the axis, of magnitude equal to that of $\Delta \theta$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A right-hand rule is used to find which way it points along the axis; if the fingers of the right hand are curled to point in the way that the object has rotated, then the thumb of the right hand points in the direction of the vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The angular velocity vector also points along the axis of rotation in the same way as the angular displacements it causes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] If a disk spins counterclockwise as seen from above, its angular velocity vector points upwards.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Similarly, the angular acceleration vector points along the axis of rotation in the same direction that the angular velocity would point if the angular acceleration were maintained for a long time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The torque vector points along the axis around which the torque tends to cause rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] To maintain rotation around a fixed axis, the total torque vector has to be along the axis, so that it only changes the magnitude and not the direction of the angular velocity vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In the case of a hinge, only the component of the torque vector along the axis has an effect on the rotation, other forces and torques are compensated by the structure.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Only two numbers, not three, are needed to define the direction of a unit vector e rooted at the origin because the magnitude of e is constrained.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] For example, the elevation and azimuth angles of e suffice to locate it in any particular Cartesian coordinate frame.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] By Rodrigues' rotation formula, the angle and axis determine a transformation that rotates three-dimensional vectors.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The rotation occurs in the sense prescribed by the right-hand rule.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The rotation axis is sometimes called the *Euler axis*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The axis–angle representation is predicated on Euler's rotation theorem, which dictates that any rotation or sequence of rotations of a rigid body in a three-dimensional space is equivalent to a pure rotation about a single fixed axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] It is one of many rotation formalisms in three dimensions.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The simplest case of rotation not around a fixed axis is that of constant angular speed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] For the example of the Earth rotating around its axis, there is very little friction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] For a fan, the motor applies a torque to compensate for friction.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Similar to the fan, equipment found in the mass production manufacturing industry demonstrate rotation around a fixed axis effectively.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] For example, a multi-spindle lathe is used to rotate the material on its axis to effectively increase the productivity of cutting, deformation and turning operations.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The angle of rotation is a linear function of time, which modulo 360° is a periodic function.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] An example of this is the two-body problem with circular orbits.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Internal tensile stress provides the centripetal force that keeps a spinning object together.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] A rigid body model neglects the accompanying strain.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] If the body is not rigid this strain will cause it to change shape.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] This is expressed as the object changing shape due to the "centrifugal force".
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Celestial bodies rotating about each other often have elliptic orbits.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The special case of circular orbits is an example of a rotation around a fixed axis: this axis is the line through the center of mass perpendicular to the plane of motion.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The centripetal force is provided by gravity, see also two-body problem.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] This usually also applies for a spinning celestial body, so it need not be solid to keep together unless the angular speed is too high in relation to its density.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] (It will, however, tend to become oblate.) For example, a spinning celestial body of water must take at least 3 hours and 18 minutes to rotate, regardless of size, or the water will separate.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] If the density of the fluid is higher the time can be less.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In geometry, a plane of rotation is an abstract object used to describe or visualize rotations in space.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In two dimensions, there is only one plane of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] In three dimensions, the plane of rotation is perpendicular to the axis of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] The main use for planes of rotation is in describing more complex rotations in four-dimensional space and higher dimensions, where they can be used to break down the rotations into simpler parts.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] This can be done using geometric algebra, with the planes of rotations associated with simple bivectors in the algebra.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] Mathematically such planes can be described in a number of ways.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] They can be described in terms of planes and angles of rotation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] They can be associated with bivectors from geometric algebra.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] They are related to the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a rotation matrix.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/rotation-around-a-fixed-axis] And in particular dimensions they are related to other algebraic and geometric properties, which can then be generalised to other dimensions.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] In physics and mechanics, **torque** is the rotational correspondent of linear force.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] It is also referred to as the **moment of force**, or simply the **moment**.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Just as a linear force is a push or a pull applied to a body, a torque can be thought of as a twist applied to an object with respect to a chosen axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] For example, when driving a screw, a screwdriver applies torque to the screw, causing it to tend to rotate around its axis.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Torque is generally referred to using different vocabulary depending on geographical location and field of study, with *torque* generally being associated with physics and *moment* being associated with engineering.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] This article follows the definition used in US physics in its usage of the word *torque*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Torque is typically represented mathematically using the lowercase Greek letter *tau* (𝜏).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] When being referred to as moment of force, it is commonly denoted by M.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The term *torque* (from Latin *torquēre*, 'to twist') is said to have been suggested by James Thomson and appeared in print in April, 1884.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Usage is attested the same year by Silvanus P.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Thompson in the first edition of *Dynamo-Electric Machinery*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] In mechanical engineering in the UK and the US, torque is generally referred to as *moment of force*, usually shortened to *moment*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] This terminology can be traced back to at least 1811 in Siméon Denis Poisson's *Traité de mécanique*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] An English translation of Poisson's work appeared in 1842.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The torque about an axis can be calculated by multiplying the linear force applied perpendicularly to a lever multiplied by its distance from the lever's fulcrum (the length of the **lever arm**).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Therefore, torque is defined as the product of the magnitude of the perpendicular component of the force and the distance of the line of action of a force from the point around which it is being determined.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] In three dimensions, the torque is a pseudovector; for point particles, it is given by the cross product of the displacement vector and the force vector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The direction of the torque can be determined by using the right-hand grip rule: if the fingers of the right hand are curled from the direction of the lever arm to the direction of the force, then the thumb points in the direction of the torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] It follows that the **torque vector** is perpendicular to both the *position* and *force* vectors, and defines the plane in which the two vectors lie.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The resulting torque vector direction is determined by the right-hand rule.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Therefore any force directed parallel to the particle's position vector does not produce a torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The magnitude of torque applied to a rigid body depends on three quantities: the force applied, the **lever arm vector** connecting the point about which the torque is being measured to the point of force application, and the angle between the force and lever arm vectors.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The SI unit for torque is the newton-meter (N⋅m).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] For more on the units of torque, see *§ Units*.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {L} }$ is the angular momentum vector and ${\textstyle t}$ is time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] where ${\textstyle I=mr^{2}}$ is the moment of inertia and ${\textstyle {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}$ is the orbital angular velocity pseudovector.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] using the derivative of a vector is ${\mathrm {d} {\hat {\boldsymbol {e}}}_{\text{i}} \over \mathrm {d} t}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}\times {\hat {\boldsymbol {e}}}_{\text{i}}$ This equation is the rotational analogue of Newton's second law for point particles, and is valid for any type of trajectory.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] In some simple cases like a rotating disc, where only the moment of inertia on rotating axis is, the rotational Newton's second law can be ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}=I{\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ where ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}={\dot {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}$ .
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The definition of angular momentum for a single point particle is: $\mathbf {L} =\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {p}$ where **p** is the particle's linear momentum and **r** is the position vector from the origin.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] This result can easily be proven by splitting the vectors into components and applying the product rule.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The cross product of momentum $\mathbf {p}$ with its associated velocity $\mathbf {v}$ is zero because velocity and momentum are parallel, so the second term vanishes.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Therefore, torque on a particle is *equal* to the first derivative of its angular momentum with respect to time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] This is a general proof for point particles, but it can be generalized to a system of point particles by applying the above proof to each of the point particles and then summing over all the point particles.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Similarly, the proof can be generalized to a continuous mass by applying the above proof to each point within the mass, and then integrating over the entire mass.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] This word is derived from the Latin word *rotātus* meaning 'to rotate'.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The term *rotatum* is not universally recognized but is commonly used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] There is not a universally accepted lexicon to indicate the successive derivatives of rotatum, even if sometimes various proposals have been made.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The law of conservation of energy can also be used to understand torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] If a force is allowed to act through a distance, it is doing mechanical work.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Similarly, if torque is allowed to act through an angular displacement, it is doing work.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] where *τ* is torque, and *θ*1 and *θ*2 represent (respectively) the initial and final angular positions of the body.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] where *I* is the moment of inertia of the body and *ω* is its angular speed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] where *P* is power, ***τ*** is torque, ***ω*** is the angular velocity, and $\cdot$ represents the scalar product.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Algebraically, the equation may be rearranged to compute torque for a given angular speed and power output.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Official SI literature indicates the **newton-meter** as the standard unit for torque, properly denoted using N⋅m; although this is dimensionally equivalent to the joule, which is not used for torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] In the case of torque, the unit is assigned to a vector, whereas for energy, it is assigned to a scalar.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] This means that the dimensional equivalence of the newton-metre and the joule may be applied in the former but not in the latter case.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] This problem is addressed in orientational analysis, which treats the radian as a base unit rather than as a dimensionless unit.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Torque has the dimension of force times distance, symbolically T−2L2M, and those fundamental dimensions are the same as that for energy or work.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The traditional imperial units for torque are the pound foot (lbf-ft), or, for small values, the pound inch (lbf-in).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] In the US, torque is most commonly referred to as the **foot-pound** (denoted as either lb-ft or ft-lb) and the **inch-pound** (denoted as in-lb).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Practitioners depend on context and the hyphen in the abbreviation to know that these refer to torque and not to energy or moment of mass (as the symbolism ft-lb would properly imply).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] A conversion factor may be necessary when using different units of power or torque.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] For example, if rotational speed (unit: revolution per minute or second) is used in place of angular speed (unit: radian per second), we must multiply by 2π radians per revolution.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] In the following formulas, *P* is power, *τ* is torque, and *ν* (Greek letter nu) is rotational speed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Dividing by 60 seconds per minute gives us the following.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] where rotational speed is in revolutions per minute (rpm, rev/min).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Some people (e.g., American automotive engineers) use horsepower (mechanical) for power, foot-pounds (lbf⋅ft) for torque and rpm for rotational speed.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The constant below (in foot-pounds per minute) changes with the definition of the horsepower; for example, using metric horsepower, it becomes approximately 32,550.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The use of other units (e.g., BTU per hour for power) would require a different custom conversion factor.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] For a rotating object, the *linear distance* covered at the circumference of rotation is the product of the radius with the angle covered.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] That is: linear distance = radius × angular distance.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] And by definition, linear distance = linear speed × time = radius × angular speed × time.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] By the definition of torque: torque = radius × force.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] We can rearrange this to determine force = torque ÷ radius.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The radius *r* and time *t* have dropped out of the equation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] However, angular speed must be in radians per unit of time, by the assumed direct relationship between linear speed and angular speed at the beginning of the derivation.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] If torque is in newton-metres and rotational speed in revolutions per second, the above equation gives power in newton-metres per second or watts.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] If Imperial units are used, and if torque is in pounds-force feet and rotational speed in revolutions per minute, the above equation gives power in foot pounds-force per minute.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The construction of the "moment arm" is shown in the figure to the right, along with the vectors **r** and **F** mentioned above.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The problem with this definition is that it does not give the direction of the torque but only the magnitude, and hence it is difficult to use in three-dimensional cases.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] If the force is perpendicular to the displacement vector **r**, the moment arm will be equal to the distance to the centre, and torque will be a maximum for the given force.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] For an object to be in static equilibrium, not only must the sum of the forces be zero, but also the sum of the torques (moments) about any point.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] For a two-dimensional situation with horizontal and vertical forces, the sum of the forces requirement is two equations: Σ*H* = 0 and Σ*V* = 0, and the torque a third equation: Σ*τ* = 0.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] That is, to solve statically determinate equilibrium problems in two-dimensions, three equations are used.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] When the net force on the system is zero, the torque measured from any point in space is the same.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] For example, the torque on a current-carrying loop in a uniform magnetic field is the same regardless of the point of reference.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Torque forms part of the basic specification of an engine: the power output of an engine is expressed as its torque multiplied by the angular speed of the drive shaft.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Internal-combustion engines produce useful torque only over a limited range of rotational speeds (typically from around 1,000–6,000 rpm for a small car).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] One can measure the varying torque output over that range with a dynamometer, and show it as a torque curve.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Steam engines and electric motors tend to produce maximum torque close to zero rpm, with the torque diminishing as rotational speed rises (due to increasing friction and other constraints).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Reciprocating steam-engines and electric motors can start heavy loads from zero rpm without a clutch.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] A cyclist, the person who rides the bicycle, provides the input power by turning pedals, thereby cranking the front sprocket (commonly referred to as chainring).
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The input power provided by the cyclist is equal to the product of angular speed (i.e. the number of pedal revolutions per minute times 2*π*) and the torque at the spindle of the bicycle's crankset.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] The bicycle's drivetrain transmits the input power to the road wheel, which in turn conveys the received power to the road as the output power of the bicycle.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Depending on the gear ratio of the bicycle, a (torque, angular speed)input pair is converted to a (torque, angular speed)output pair.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] By using a larger rear gear, or by switching to a lower gear in multi-speed bicycles, angular speed of the road wheels is decreased while the torque is increased, product of which (i.e. power) does not change.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Torque can be multiplied via three methods: by locating the fulcrum such that the length of a lever is increased; by using a longer lever; or by the use of a speed-reducing gearset or gear box.
[src:rigid-body-dynamics-physics/torque] Such a mechanism multiplies torque, as rotation rate is reduced.
